[src:t5-model/language-model] A **language model** is a computational model that predicts sequences in natural language.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Large language models (LLMs), currently their most advanced form as of 2026, are predominantly based on transformers trained on larger datasets (frequently using texts scraped from the public internet).
[src:t5-model/language-model] They have superseded recurrent neural network-based models, which had previously superseded the purely statistical models, such as the word *n*-gram language model.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Noam Chomsky did pioneering work on language models in the 1950s by developing a theory of formal grammars.
[src:t5-model/language-model] In 1980, statistical approaches were explored and found to be more useful for many purposes than rule-based formal grammars.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Discrete representations like word *n*-gram language models, with probabilities for discrete combinations of words, made significant advances.
[src:t5-model/language-model] In the 2000s, continuous representations for words, such as word embeddings, began to replace discrete representations.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes a word’s meaning such that words closer in vector space are similar in meaning and common relationships between words, such as plurality or gender, are preserved.
[src:t5-model/language-model] A word *n*-gram language model is a statistical model of language which calculates the probability of the next word in a sequence from a fixed size window of previous words.
[src:t5-model/language-model] If one previous word is considered, it is a bigram model; if two words, a trigram model; if *n* − 1 words, an *n*-gram model.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Special tokens are introduced to denote the start and end of a sentence $\langle s\rangle$ and $\langle /s\rangle$ .
[src:t5-model/language-model] To prevent a zero probability being assigned to unseen words, the probability of each seen word is slightly lowered to make room for the unseen words in a given corpus.
[src:t5-model/language-model] To achieve this, various smoothing methods are used, from simple "add-one" smoothing (assigning a count of 1 to unseen *n*-grams, as an uninformative prior) to more sophisticated techniques, such as Good–Turing discounting or back-off models.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Word *n-*gram models have largely been superseded by recurrent neural network–based models, which in turn have been superseded by Transformer-based models often referred to as large language models.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Maximum entropy language models encode the relationship between a word and the *n*-gram history using feature functions.
[src:t5-model/language-model] where $Z(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m-1})$ is the partition function, a is the parameter vector, and $f(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m})$ is the feature function.
[src:t5-model/language-model] In the simplest case, the feature function is just an indicator of the presence of a certain *n*-gram.
[src:t5-model/language-model] It is helpful to use a prior on a or some form of regularization.
[src:t5-model/language-model] The log-bilinear model is another example of an exponential language model.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Skip-gram language model is an attempt at overcoming the data sparsity problem that the preceding model (i.e. word *n*-gram language model) faced.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Words represented in an embedding vector were not necessarily consecutive anymore, but could leave gaps that are *skipped* over (thus the name "skip-gram").
[src:t5-model/language-model] Formally, a k-skip-n-gram is a length-n subsequence where the components occur at distance at most k from each other.
[src:t5-model/language-model] In skip-gram model, semantic relations between words are represented by linear combinations, capturing a form of compositionality.
[src:t5-model/language-model] where ≈ is made precise by stipulating that its right-hand side must be the nearest neighbor of the value of the left-hand side.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Continuous representations or embeddings of words are produced in recurrent neural network-based language models (known also as *continuous space language models*).
[src:t5-model/language-model] Such continuous space embeddings help to alleviate the curse of dimensionality, which is the consequence of the number of possible sequences of words increasing exponentially with the size of the vocabulary, further causing a data sparsity problem.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Neural networks avoid this problem by representing words as non-linear combinations of weights in a neural net.
[src:t5-model/language-model] A large language model (LLM) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:t5-model/language-model] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:t5-model/language-model] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:t5-model/language-model] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Although sometimes matching human performance, it is not clear whether they are plausible cognitive models.
[src:t5-model/language-model] At least for recurrent neural networks, it has been shown that they sometimes learn patterns that humans do not, but fail to learn patterns that humans typically do.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Evaluation of the quality of language models is mostly done by comparison to human created sample benchmarks created from typical language-oriented tasks.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Other, less established, quality tests examine the intrinsic character of a language model or compare two such models.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Since language models are typically intended to be dynamic and to learn from data they see, some proposed models investigate the rate of learning, e.g., through inspection of learning curves.
[src:t5-model/language-model] Various data sets have been developed for use in evaluating language processing systems.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] While it is widely agreed that the output of any NLG process is text, there is some disagreement about whether the inputs of an NLG system need to be non-linguistic.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Common applications of NLG methods include the production of various reports, for example weather and patient reports; image captions; and chatbots like ChatGPT.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Automated NLG can be compared to the process humans use when they turn ideas into writing or speech.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Psycholinguists prefer the term language production for this process, which can also be described in mathematical terms, or modeled in a computer for psychological research.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG systems can also be compared to translators of artificial computer languages, such as decompilers or transpilers, which also produce human-readable code generated from an intermediate representation.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Human languages tend to be considerably more complex and allow for much more ambiguity and variety of expression than programming languages, which makes NLG more challenging.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The practical considerations in building NLU vs.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLU needs to deal with ambiguous or erroneous user input, whereas the ideas the system wants to express through NLG are generally known precisely.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG needs to choose a specific, self-consistent textual representation from many potential representations, whereas NLU generally tries to produce a single, normalized representation of the idea expressed.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG has existed since ELIZA was developed in the mid 1960s, but the methods were first used commercially in the 1990s.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG techniques range from simple template-based systems like a mail merge that generates form letters, to systems that have a complex understanding of human grammar.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG can also be accomplished by training a statistical model using machine learning, typically on a large corpus of human-written texts.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The *Pollen Forecast for Scotland* system is a simple example of a simple NLG system that could essentially be based on a template.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] This system takes as input six numbers, which give predicted pollen levels in different parts of Scotland.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] From these numbers, the system generates a short textual summary of pollen levels as its output.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Comparing these two illustrates some of the choices that NLG systems must make; these are further discussed below.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The process to generate text can be as simple as keeping a list of canned text that is copied and pasted, possibly linked with some glue text.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The results may be satisfactory in simple domains such as horoscope machines or generators of personalized business letters.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] However, a sophisticated NLG system needs to include stages of planning and merging of information to enable the generation of text that looks natural and does not become repetitive.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Deciding what information to mention in the text.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] For instance, in the pollen example above, deciding whether to explicitly mention that pollen level is 7 in the southeast.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Overall organisation of the information to convey.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] For example, deciding to describe the areas with high pollen levels first, instead of the areas with low pollen levels.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Merging of similar sentences to improve readability and naturalness.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] should be used when describing a pollen level of 4.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] to refer to a certain region in Scotland.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] An alternative approach to NLG is to use "end-to-end" machine learning to build a system, without having separate stages as above.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] In other words, we build an NLG system by training a machine learning algorithm (often an LSTM) on a large data set of input data and corresponding (human-written) output texts.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The end-to-end approach has perhaps been most successful in image captioning, that is automatically generating a textual caption for an image.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] From a commercial perspective, the most successful NLG applications have been *data-to-text* systems which generate textual summaries of databases and data sets; these systems usually perform data analysis as well as text generation.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Research has shown that textual summaries can be more effective than graphs and other visuals for decision support, and that computer-generated texts can be superior (from the reader's perspective) to human-written texts.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The first commercial data-to-text systems produced weather forecasts from weather data.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The earliest such system to be deployed was FoG, which was used by Environment Canada to generate weather forecasts in French and English in the early 1990s.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The success of FoG triggered other work, both research and commercial.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Recent applications include the UK Met Office's text-enhanced forecast.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Data-to-text systems have since been applied in a range of settings.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Following the minor earthquake near Beverly Hills, California on March 17, 2014, The Los Angeles Times reported details about the time, location and strength of the quake within 3 minutes of the event.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] This report was automatically generated by a 'robo-journalist', which converted the incoming data into text via a preset template.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Currently there is considerable commercial interest in using NLG to summarise financial and business data.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Indeed, Gartner has said that NLG will become a standard feature of 90% of modern BI and analytics platforms.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG is also being used commercially in automated journalism, chatbots, generating product descriptions for e-commerce sites, summarising medical records, and enhancing accessibility (for example by describing graphs and data sets to blind people).
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] An example of an interactive use of NLG is the WYSIWYM framework.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] It stands for *What you see is what you meant* and allows users to see and manipulate the continuously rendered view (NLG output) of an underlying formal language document (NLG input), thereby editing the formal language without learning it.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Looking ahead, the current progress in data-to-text generation paves the way for tailoring texts to specific audiences.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] For example, data from babies in neonatal care can be converted into text differently in a clinical setting, with different levels of technical detail and explanatory language, depending on intended recipient of the text (doctor, nurse, patient).
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The same idea can be applied in a sports setting, with different reports generated for fans of specific teams.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Over the past few years, there has been an increased interest in automatically generating captions for images, as part of a broader endeavor to investigate the interface between vision and language.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A case of data-to-text generation, the algorithm of image captioning (or automatic image description) involves taking an image, analyzing its visual content, and generating a textual description (typically a sentence) that verbalizes the most prominent aspects of the image.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] An image captioning system involves two sub-tasks.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] In Image Analysis, features and attributes of an image are detected and labelled, before mapping these outputs to linguistic structures.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Recent research utilize*s* deep learning approaches through features from a pre-trained convolutional neural network such as AlexNet, VGG or Caffe, where caption generators use an activation layer from the pre-trained network as their input features.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Text Generation, the second task, is performed using a wide range of techniques.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] For example, in the Midge system, input images are represented as triples consisting of object/stuff detections, action/pose detections and spatial relations.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] These are subsequently mapped to <noun, verb, preposition> triples and realized using a tree substitution grammar.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A common method in image captioning is to use a vision model (such as a ResNet) to encode an image into a vector, then use a language model (such as an RNN) to decode the vector into a caption.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Despite advancements, challenges and opportunities remain in image capturing research.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Other open challenges include visual question-answering (VQA), as well as the construction and evaluation multilingual repositories for image description.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Another area where NLG has been widely applied is automated dialogue systems, frequently in the form of chatbots.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A chatbot or chatterbot is a software application used to conduct an on-line chat conversation via text or text-to-speech, in lieu of providing direct contact with a live human agent.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] While natural language processing (NLP) techniques are applied in deciphering human input, NLG informs the output part of the chatbot algorithms in facilitating real-time dialogues.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Early chatbot systems, including Cleverbot created by Rollo Carpenter in 1988 and published in 1997, reply to questions by identifying how a human has responded to the same question in a conversation database using information retrieval (IR) techniques.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Modern chatbot systems predominantly rely on machine learning (ML) models, such as sequence-to-sequence learning and reinforcement learning to generate natural language output.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] For example, the Alibaba shopping assistant first uses an IR approach to retrieve the best candidates from the knowledge base, then uses the ML-driven seq2seq model re-rank the candidate responses and generate the answer.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Creative language generation by NLG has been hypothesized since the field's origins.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A recent pioneer in the area is Phillip Parker, who has developed an arsenal of algorithms capable of automatically generating textbooks, crossword puzzles, poems and books on topics ranging from bookbinding to cataracts.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] The advent of large pretrained transformer-based language models such as GPT-3 has also enabled breakthroughs, with such models demonstrating recognizable ability for creating-writing tasks.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A related area of NLG application is computational humor production.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] JAPE (Joke Analysis and Production Engine) is one of the earliest large, automated humor production systems that uses a hand-coded template-based approach to create punning riddles for children.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] HAHAcronym creates humorous reinterpretations of any given acronym, as well as proposing new fitting acronyms given some keywords.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Despite progresses, many challenges remain in producing automated creative and humorous content that rival human output.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] In an experiment for generating satirical headlines, outputs of their best BERT-based model were perceived as funny 9.4% of the time (while real headlines from *The Onion* were 38.4%) and a GPT-2 model fine-tuned on satirical headlines achieved 6.9%.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] It has been pointed out that two main issues with humor-generation systems are the lack of annotated data sets and the lack of formal evaluation methods, which could be applicable to other creative content generation.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Some have argued relative to other applications, there has been a lack of attention to creative aspects of language production within NLG.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] NLG researchers stand to benefit from insights into what constitutes creative language production, as well as structural features of narrative that have the potential to improve NLG output even in data-to-text systems.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] As in other scientific fields, NLG researchers need to test how well their systems, modules, and algorithms work.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] An ultimate goal is how useful NLG systems are at helping people, which is the first of the above techniques.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] However, task-based evaluations are time-consuming and expensive, and can be difficult to carry out (especially if they require subjects with specialised expertise, such as doctors).
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Hence (as in other areas of NLP) task-based evaluations are the exception, not the norm.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Recently researchers are assessing how well human-ratings and metrics correlate with (predict) task-based evaluations.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Work is being conducted in the context of Generation Challenges shared-task events.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] Initial results suggest that human ratings are much better than metrics in this regard.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] In other words, human ratings usually do predict task-effectiveness at least to some degree (although there are exceptions), while ratings produced by metrics often do not predict task-effectiveness well.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] In any case, human ratings are the most popular evaluation technique in NLG; this is contrast to machine translation, where metrics are widely used.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] An AI can be graded on *faithfulness* to its training data or, alternatively, on *factuality*.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A response that reflects the training data but not reality is faithful but not factual.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] A confident but unfaithful response is a *hallucination*.
[src:t5-model/natural-language-generation] In Natural Language Processing, a hallucination is often defined as "generated content that is nonsensical or unfaithful to the provided source content".
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] seq2seq is an approach to machine translation (or more generally, sequence transduction) with roots in information theory, where communication is understood as an encode-transmit-decode process, and machine translation can be studied as a special case of communication.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] This viewpoint was elaborated, for example, in the noisy channel model of machine translation.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In practice, seq2seq maps an input sequence into a real-numerical vector by using a neural network (the *encoder*), and then maps it back to an output sequence using another neural network (the *decoder*).
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The idea of encoder-decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The papers most commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two papers from 2014.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In the seq2seq as proposed by them, both the encoder and the decoder were LSTMs.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] This had the "bottleneck" problem, since the encoding vector has a fixed size, so for long input sequences, information would tend to be lost, as they are difficult to fit into the fixed-length encoding vector.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The attention mechanism, proposed in 2014, resolved the bottleneck problem.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] They called their model *RNNsearch*, as it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] A problem with seq2seq models at this point was that recurrent neural networks are difficult to parallelize.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The 2017 publication of Transformers resolved the problem by replacing the encoding RNN with self-attention Transformer blocks ("encoder blocks"), and the decoding RNN with cross-attention causally-masked Transformer blocks ("decoder blocks").
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] One of the papers cited as the originator for seq2seq is (Sutskever et al 2014), published at Google Brain while they were on Google's machine translation project.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The research allowed Google to overhaul Google Translate into Google Neural Machine Translation in 2016.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Mikolov had worked on RNNLM (using RNN for language modelling) for his PhD thesis, and is more notable for developing word2vec.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The encoder is responsible for processing the input sequence and capturing its essential information, which is stored as the hidden state of the network and, in a model with attention mechanism, a context vector.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The context vector is the weighted sum of the input hidden states and is generated for every time instance in the output sequences.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The decoder takes the context vector and hidden states from the encoder and generates the final output sequence.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The decoder operates in an autoregressive manner, producing one element of the output sequence at a time.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] At each step, it considers the previously generated elements, the context vector, and the input sequence information to make predictions for the next element in the output sequence.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Specifically, in a model with attention mechanism, the context vector and the hidden state are concatenated together to form an attention hidden vector, which is used as an input for the decoder.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The seq2seq method developed in the early 2010s uses two neural networks: an encoder network converts an input sentence into numerical vectors, and a decoder network converts those vectors to sentences in the target language.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The Attention mechanism was grafted onto this structure in 2014 and is shown below.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Later it was refined into the encoder-decoder Transformer architecture of 2017.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] There is a subtle difference between training and prediction.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] During training time, both the input and the output sequences are known.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] During prediction time, only the input sequence is known, and the output sequence must be decoded by the network itself.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Specifically, consider an input sequence $x_{1:n}$ and output sequence $y_{1:m}$ .
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The encoder would process the input $x_{1:n}$ step by step.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] After that, the decoder would take the output from the encoder, as well as the <bos> as input, and produce a prediction ${\hat {y}}_{1}$ .
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Now, the question is: what should be input to the decoder in the next step?
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] A standard method for training is "teacher forcing".
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In teacher forcing, no matter what is output by the decoder, the next input to the decoder is always the reference.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] That is, even if ${\hat {y}}_{1}\neq y_{1}$ , the next input to the decoder is still $y_{1}$ , and so on.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] During prediction time, the "teacher" $y_{1:m}$ would be unavailable.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Therefore, the input to the decoder must be ${\hat {y}}_{1}$ , then ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ , and so on.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] It is found that if a model is trained purely by teacher forcing, its performance would degrade during prediction time, since generation based on the model's own output is different from generation based on the teacher's output.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] This is called exposure bias or a train/test distribution shift.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] A 2015 paper recommends that, during training, randomly switch between teacher forcing and no teacher forcing.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The attention mechanism is an enhancement introduced by Bahdanau et al. in 2014 to address limitations in the basic Seq2Seq architecture where a longer input sequence results in the hidden state output of the encoder becoming irrelevant for the decoder.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] It enables the model to selectively focus on different parts of the input sequence during the decoding process.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] At each decoder step, an alignment model calculates the attention score using the current decoder state and all of the attention hidden vectors as input.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] An alignment model is another neural network model that is trained jointly with the seq2seq model used to calculate how well an input, represented by the hidden state, matches with the previous output, represented by attention hidden state.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] A softmax function is then applied to the attention score to get the attention weight.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In some models, the encoder states are directly fed into an activation function, removing the need for alignment model.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] An activation function receives one decoder state and one encoder state and returns a scalar value of their relevance.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Consider the seq2seq language English-to-French translation task.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] To be concrete, let us consider the translation of "the zone of international control <end>", which should translate to "la zone de contrôle international <end>".
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Here, we use the special <end> token as a control character to delimit the end of input for both the encoder and the decoder.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] An input sequence of text $x_{0},x_{1},\dots$ is processed by a neural network (which can be an LSTM, a Transformer encoder, or some other network) into a sequence of real-valued vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ , where h stands for "hidden vector".
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] After the encoder has finished processing, the decoder starts operating over the hidden vectors, to produce an output sequence $y_{0},y_{1},\dots$ , autoregressively.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Here, we use the special <start> token as a control character to delimit the start of input for the decoder.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The decoding terminates as soon as "<end>" appears in the decoder output.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] As hand-crafting weights defeats the purpose of machine learning, the model must compute the attention weights on its own.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Taking analogy from the language of database queries, we make the model construct a triple of vectors: key, query, and value.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The rough idea is that we have a "database" in the form of a list of key-value pairs.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The decoder sends in a **query**, and obtains a reply in the form of a weighted sum of the **values**, where the weight is proportional to how closely the query resembles each **key**.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The decoder first processes the "<start>" input partially, to obtain an intermediate vector $h_{0}^{d}$ , the 0th hidden vector of decoder.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Then, the intermediate vector is transformed by a linear map $W^{Q}$ into a **query** vector $q_{0}=h_{0}^{d}W^{Q}$ .
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Meanwhile, the hidden vectors outputted by the encoder are transformed by another linear map $W^{K}$ into **key** vectors $k_{0}=h_{0}W^{K},k_{1}=h_{1}W^{K},\dots$ .
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The linear maps are useful for providing the model with enough freedom to find the best way to represent the data.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Ideally, the model should have learned to compute the keys and values, such that $q_{0}k_{0}^{T}$ is large, $q_{0}k_{1}^{T}$ is small, and the rest are very small.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] This can be interpreted as saying that the attention weight should be mostly applied to the 0th hidden vector of the encoder, a little to the 1st, and essentially none to the rest.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In order to make a properly weighted sum, we need to transform this list of dot products into a probability distribution over $0,1,\dots$ .
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] where $v_{0}=h_{0}W^{V},v_{1}=h_{1}W^{V},\dots$ are the **value** vectors, linearly transformed by another matrix to provide the model with freedom to find the best way to represent values.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Without the matrices $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ , the model would be forced to use the same hidden vector for both key and value, which might not be appropriate, as these two tasks are not the same.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The particular version described in this section is "decoder cross-attention", as the output context vector is used by the decoder, and the input keys and values come from the encoder, but the query comes from the decoder, thus "cross-attention".
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Note that the querying vector, $h_{0}^{d}$ , is not necessarily the same as the key-value vector $h_{0}$ .
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In fact, it is theoretically possible for query, key, and value vectors to all be different, though that is rarely done in practice.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In 2019, Facebook announced its use in symbolic integration and resolution of differential equations.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The company claimed that it could solve complex equations more rapidly and with greater accuracy than commercial solutions such as Mathematica, MATLAB and Maple.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] First, the equation is parsed into a tree structure to avoid notational idiosyncrasies.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] An LSTM neural network then applies its standard pattern recognition facilities to process the tree.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In 2020, Google released Meena, a 2.6 billion parameter seq2seq-based chatbot trained on a 341 GB data set.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Google claimed that the chatbot has 1.7 times greater model capacity than OpenAI's GPT-2.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] In 2022, Amazon introduced AlexaTM 20B, a moderate-sized (20 billion parameter) seq2seq language model.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] It uses an encoder-decoder to accomplish few-shot learning.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The encoder outputs a representation of the input that the decoder uses as input to perform a specific task, such as translating the input into another language.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] The model outperforms the much larger GPT-3 in language translation and summarization.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] Training mixes denoising (appropriately inserting missing text in strings) and causal-language-modeling (meaningfully extending an input text).
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] It allows adding features across different languages without massive training workflows.
[src:t5-model/seq2seq] AlexaTM 20B achieved state-of-the-art performance in few-shot-learning tasks across all Flores-101 language pairs, outperforming GPT-3 on several tasks.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] T5 models are usually pretrained on a massive dataset of text and code, after which they can perform the text-based tasks that are similar to their pretrained tasks.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] They can also be finetuned to perform other tasks.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] T5 models have been employed in various applications, including chatbots, machine translation systems, text summarization tools, code generation, and robotics.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The original T5 models are pre-trained on the Colossal Clean Crawled Corpus (C4), containing text and code scraped from the internet.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] This pre-training process enables the models to learn general language understanding and generation abilities.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] T5 models can then be fine-tuned on specific downstream tasks, adapting their knowledge to perform well in various applications.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The T5 models were pretrained on many tasks, all in the format of `<input text>` -> `<output text>`.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The T5 series encompasses several models with varying sizes and capabilities, all encoder-decoder Transformers, where the encoder processes the input text, and the decoder generates the output text.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] These models are often distinguished by their parameter count, which indicates the complexity and potential capacity of the model.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] Note that unlike typical Transformers, the 3B and 11B models do not satisfy $d_{\text{model}}=d_{\text{kv}}n_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] Compared to the original Transformer, it uses a few minor modifications: layer normalization with no additive bias; placing the layer normalization outside the residual path; relative positional embedding.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] For all experiments, they used a WordPiece tokenizer, with vocabulary size 32,000.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The tokenizer is shared across both the input and output of each model.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] It was trained on a mixture of English, German, French, and Romanian data from the C4 dataset, at a ratio of 10:1:1:1.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] Several subsequent models used the T5 architecture, with non-standardized naming conventions used to differentiate them.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] This section attempts to collect the main ones.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] An exhaustive list of the variants released by Google Brain is on the GitHub repo for T5X.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] Some models are trained from scratch while others are trained by starting with a previous trained model.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] By default, each model is trained from scratch, except otherwise noted.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The T5 model itself is an encoder-decoder model, allowing it to be used for instruction following.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The encoder encodes the instruction, and the decoder autoregressively generates the reply.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] The T5 encoder can be used as a text encoder, much like BERT.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] It encodes a text into a sequence of real-number vectors, which can be used for downstream applications.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] For example, Google Imagen uses *T5-XXL* as text encoder, and the encoded text vectors are used as conditioning on a diffusion model.
[src:t5-model/t5-language-model] As another example, the AuraFlow diffusion model uses *Pile-T5-XL*.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:t5-model/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:t5-model/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
